              <div class="dtlh1 span12 medium">	Creating the Project
							</div>
							<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
              	Media is what makes filmmo different, and, if you can’t tell already, we think different. Having media in your project makes it so much better than writing a simple sentence or two about the people that you want. It’s your chance to tell a story or convey an emotion; it also tells people you are serious about making it happen.
								<br><br>
								When you write about your project, talk about it as you would to your friends. You don’t need to be a writer to explain to other people why you started your film.  So tell people about your experiences or motivations for your film like a story. We all like hearing a good story, and filmmo is about getting great stories created and shared.</div>
								<br><br>
								<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Draft Settings
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">

								Creativity, innovation, ideas; they make the world we live in amazing. They fuel artistic vision and inspire us to do amazing things. Our brains are incredible at coming up with original thoughts, but have some trouble when it comes to remembering what we were thinking when that vision struck us.
								<br><br>
								When an idea strikes, it’s best to move on it quickly and start jotting down your thoughts for the film and the people you would need to do it.  Draft mode was added so you can do just that while keeping your idea private until it’s ready to be shared.  While in Draft mode you can edit your project details, figure out the budget and decide who to involve. Plus it’s motivating to know that Pre-Production status is just around the corner from Draft mode.
								</div>
								<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Choosing Your Image
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									<img src="/assets/labs1.jpg" class="img-rounded" align="right" alt="" />
									This is how you represent yourself to the rest of the filmmo community, and picking the best image you can shows you are serious about creating something great. Projects that use professional-looking media often attract producers with more talented cast and crew. <b>You know how it goes, appearances are everything!</b>
									</div>
									<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Setting Dates
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									<img src="/assets/labs2.jpg" class="img-rounded" align="right" alt="" />
									Important dates are not just for your fans and team to see when things are going down, they are vital tools for you. While sometimes it’s nice to be on island time, the reality is we all have deadlines. Setting milestones to hit are great ways to keep you motivated and on-time throughout your project.				</div>
									<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Cast and Crew
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									<img src="/assets/labs3.jpg" class="img-rounded" align="right" alt="" />
									Casting is probably one of the funnest parts of making a film, but it’s no fun at all when you don’t have the right people to choose from. One of filmmo’s biggest challenges was to make a simple yet powerful system that anyone would feel comfortable on. We give you the tools, you make the decisions.
									<br><br>
									Casting is not always as complicated as people lead on, but knowing who you are working with is incredibly important.  Check your potential cast out: Watch their demo reel or clips, read endorsements about their skill sets, see what they’ve done before.  Intuition can tell us when someone is a good fit, but a person’s experience is easier to evaluate when its all laid out on their profile. We give you the tools to do your homework so you know what you are getting when you cast and crew.
									<br><br>
									filmmo is not about getting as many people as possible to bombard you with requests to be a part of the project, it’s about getting the right people.  filmmo puts the project creator in charge by offering tools to manage applicants at your pace.  We try to make casting a little less like hailing a cab and more like getting an Uber; you know exactly what you are going to get. Casting/Crewing through traditional means can also be time consuming and expensive, two things that filmmakers hate. Budgets are probably the biggest dictators of what you can and cannot do, they are a painful reality. filmmo saves you time and money so you can spend them on things that matter, like shopping for the right champagne for your wrap party.</div>
									<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Paying Your Team
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									
									What people make is dependent upon a lot of factors, sometimes it’s what you decide, sometimes it’s what the law decides. There are a number of Guilds that operate in the filmmaking industry; some of the main unions in the United States are SAG-AFTRA, IATSE, and WGA to name a few. All of the major union pay rates can be seen here in the Resources section. If you are hiring non-union cast/crew, you must still adhere to <a href="http://www.dol.gov/whd/minwage/america.htm.">all state minimum wage guidlines</a>. These resources are meant to be a helpful start in managing your payroll, but are not a comprehensive guide. You are responsible for understanding the individual guidelines and ordinaces for what you operate in.
									<br><br>
									You can find incredibly talented film industry professionals outside of the unions, such as people in film school or freelancing.  There are plenty of examples of these emerging filmmakers going on to win Academy Awards, so it’s important not to discredit their value.  A good rule of thumb is to pay people fairly; you often get better results and end up saving money in the long run.  Keep in mind that non-union cast/crew don’t have a big union behind them pushing for fair pay.  You’ll find you spend more time and money trying to fix problems with an underpaid cast and crew, do it right from the start.
									</div>
									<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Getting What you Give
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									
									Copy and credit means you “pay” your actors with a copy of the DVD and they get credits with footage to include in their reel. Deferred pay means the team may get paid, but only if the film makes a profit. Copy and credit deals have always been around and have literally helped thousands of people break into the industry.
									<br><br>
									filmmo’s goal is to promote fair treatment of artists and crew in the industry, and users reported to be taking advantage of people will be banned from using filmmo.  In competitive areas like Los Angeles, you can always find a lot of people who will work for fairly inexpensive rates, but that should not be an invitation to abuse their dedication. You get what you give, so be fair to emerging talent. The people you meet climbing up the ladder are the same people you meet going down.
									</div>
									<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Marketing
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									<img src="/assets/labs4.jpg" class="img-rounded" align="right" alt="" />
									Have you ever wanted to see the behind-the-scenes of a film as it’s being made? Want to hear some cool production stories? Well, we did too.
									<br><br>
									About 90% of internet traffic is video-related, so as more and more people turn to consuming content online, it makes sense to have a way to engage fans throughout the process of the film’s creation. Traditionally there is a disconnect between the filmmaker and the fan that is detrimental to the process. By having a dedicated platform for filmmakers, you can build a following that wants to view and share your video when it’s done without having to compete for attention on Twitter and Facebook.
									<br><br>
									It’s not uncommon for big studios to spend half or more of the film’s production budget on Print and Advertising (P&A).  Studios use an incredibly outdated and inefficient marketing strategies. By waiting until the film is basically done to do a huge marketing push, they are missing out on getting fans for a lot less money. Honestly, whoever went to a flick because they saw it on the side of a bus?   
									<br><br>
									filmmo pioneered the idea of Early Stage Fan Engagement when we saw how inefficiently film budget’s were used. With project on filmmo, you can build up fans early in the process and have them engaged with you as things progress. This saves you money on trying to do a huge marketing push 2 weeks away from release, because you already have an audience who wants to see your film.  
									</div>
									<div class="dtlh1 span12 small">
									Pictures and Video	
									</div>
									<div class="featuretext span12 light light">
									<img src="/assets/labs5.jpg" class="img-rounded" align="right" alt="" />									
									People love pics and video, so uploading really good shots is a great way to keep fans engaged.
									<br><br>
									Your blog is NOT like your Facebook wall; you are the only one who can post updates on your profile or project.  We did this intentionally to give you control of what people see about your project.  This is not a place for trolls, rather a dedicated place to showcase your work and engage fans. The internet is so full of distractions that it really is hard to get a place to find dedicated film fans.
									<br><br>
									You can post on your Twitter or Facebook, but unless your fans only follow you, it’s really easy for your content to get lost in all the non-film related traffic. filmmo distills all of your core value props to your fans in a simple yet visually stunning experience.
									
									
							</div>
							
              
              
              </div>
