                <div class="dtltext span12">
                  <div class="dtlinfoh regular">Building Business</div>
                  <div class="dtlinfotext regular">
                  	Creating a great piece of promotional video is key; a high-impact teaser is one of the most valuable assets you can have.  This promo video does three things really well for your business: Increases sales, establishes trust, and gets traffic on your site.  With all of the benefits of video, it is shocking how few businesses use it or how little they invest when they do.  With video appearing higher in search results and making viewers about 75% more likely to buy a product*, a better question is: Can you afford not to have a well-produced video?

										<br><br>
										There are thousands of applications for video, from a real estate agent wanting to showcase a home to a young startup looking to make a 60-second explainer video. <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZUG9qYTJMsI">One of the most successful viral video campaigns ever</a> made was produced on a $4,500 budget. As a business owner or employee in a small company, you often get the “joy” of wearing a lot of hats. When the subject of producing a video comes up at the next meeting, you might not know where to even begin. Now you do. That was one of the inspirations for filmmo, people need to a place to find vetted  filmmakers. We tried Craigslist, but it was just way too hit or miss and took forever to look through all of the people. Fortunately, filmmo makes it a lot easier to find the right people to make your film happen.
										<br><br>

										When you think about the reality of what it takes to produce a video, you realize there are a lot of moving parts to make it work. But with filmmo, we give you options: produce it yourself or hire a producer.
										<br><br>
										<div class="dtlinfoh regular small">1. Self-produce</div>

										If you are choosing this route, you should be savvy with technology, creative, and have lots of free time. Start by following along in this guide, and also realize there are several key positions you will need to fill:
										<br><br>
										<ul>
											<li><b>Director of Photography (DP)</b> this person films and should be able to do some    lighting</li><br>
												<li><b>Audio Department</b> Sound is about 70% of your film, make sure to bring on a good specialist who can handle recording audio.</li><br>
											<li><b>Editor</b> This person takes all of the footage and makes it nice. You might here the saying “we’ll fix it in post” this is the person that actually has to fix it.</li><br>
											<li><b>Actors</b> Getting a trained actor vs trying to hiring your Uncle Donny differentiates the amateurs from the pro’s. Know how and where to spend your money, and the cast is important, seriously.</li>
											</ul>
											<br><br>
										You will need to have a vision of what you want, but don’t be afraid to ask for creative input. Also remember to negotiate and fix all pay rates upfront, and be sure to visit the Resources section to find the proper agreements to use when hiring freelance filmmakers.  
										<br><br>
										Making your video will be fun, but realize everything will take much longer than you expect it. Plan ahead as much as possible, and count on things going wrong. There is no secret formula to produce a great video for your business, but keeping it simple never hurt!
										<br><br>
										
										<div class="dtlinfoh regular small">2. Hire a producer</div>

										This is a great route if you can afford it and/or don’t have the time or resources to put the production together.  Hiring a producer off the bat sometimes makes a lot more sense and can save people money in the long run.  Some people learn the hard way and try to save money cutting corners while producing it themselves.  In the end, they’re not satisfied with the finished product and have to start over. If they had a pro from the start, some of the ever-present pitfalls may have been avoided.
										<br><br>
										As in self-producing, it helps to have an idea of what you want, while seeking creative input. Also remember to negotiate to all pay rates upfront, and be sure to visit the Resources section to find the proper agreements to use when hiring a producer.
										<br><br>
										Regardless of the route you choose, we advise you to stick to a few key things:
										<br><br><ul><li>
										<b>1.Write your own script.</b> No one really knows your company like you do. It’s not a bad idea to bring someone on to proof it or adjust your copy, but your words should be at the core of your message.
										</li><br><li>
										<b>2. Don’t set out to make a viral video campaign.</b> When you look at some of the top marketing campaigns, the conversation never started with “Let’s make a viral video”. The heart of the video was making something worth watching. Use humor, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XpaOjMXyJGk">tell a touching story</a>, create something exciting; your viewers will want to spread the word.		</li>
										</ul><br><br>
										You can check out <a href="https://vimeo.com/69262690">filmmo’s explainer video</a> if you want to see some examples of what we think a good video looks like. Remember, it’s about telling great stories, so write out your script like you’re talking to people. While sometimes animation can be more effective, it’s a call you have to make for what style of video you want to create. Regardless of the route you take, filmmo gives you the tools to make your idea into a reality.<br><br>
                </div>
                </div>
              </article>
